    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:bd0b0e0f-8386-46bb-bfac-1ffa2a59b4eb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 10-year-old boy who appears younger than his stated age, slightly fidgety from the moment he enters the examination room. He has bright, curious eyes that dart around the room, examining every poster and piece of equipment before the consultation even begins. He is wearing a graphic T-shirt featuring his favorite video game characters, and his shoelaces are untied — something his mother points out with a weary but loving smile. He is of average height and weight for his age, with a few small scrapes on his knees from recent outdoor play.\n\n{patientName} lives with his mother, father, and younger sister in a suburban home. He attends 4th grade at a local primary school, where his teachers describe him as \"bright but difficult to manage in class.\" He frequently calls out answers without being asked, struggles to sit still during lessons, and often loses his homework, pencils, and school materials. He enjoys drawing, building with LEGO, and playing football with friends in the neighborhood — activities that allow him to channel his boundless energy. He has a close group of friends but sometimes clashes with peers due to impulsive behavior.\n\nAt home, {patientName}'s parents report that he has great difficulty completing tasks independently — whether homework, chores, or getting ready for school in the morning. He is easily distracted by background noise, frequently forgets instructions, and often shifts from one unfinished activity to another. Bedtime routines are a nightly struggle, as he is unable to wind down easily. His parents have expressed significant stress and frustration, and have been seeking guidance from his school counselor for the past year.\n\n{patientName} is generally cheerful and sociable, though he can become emotionally reactive when frustrated, sometimes throwing brief tantrums before quickly recovering. He does not exhibit signs of sadness, anxiety, or withdrawal. His appetite is good and he enjoys a broad range of foods. His sleep is somewhat disrupted — he takes approximately 45–60 minutes to fall asleep most nights and wakes occasionally."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e2403bc2-696a-4cdd-b94f-f97d2b77be8b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at 39 weeks via uncomplicated vaginal delivery. Neonatal period was uneventful. Developmental milestones were met, though his parents retrospectively note he was always a \"high-energy\" toddler. Speech and language development were normal. He has no history of head trauma, seizures, or significant neurological illness.\n\nConcerns about attention and behavior were first raised by his kindergarten teacher at age 6. A school-based assessment at age 8 noted significant difficulties with sustained attention, task completion, and behavioral self-regulation. A formal developmental-behavioral pediatrics evaluation is currently underway. There is no prior psychiatric hospitalization or pharmacological treatment for ADHD to date.\n\nComorbidities include mild allergic rhinitis, managed seasonally. He has had the standard childhood immunization schedule completed up to date. He was hospitalized briefly at age 4 for a febrile seizure (single episode, no recurrence, no antiepileptic treatment required). He has no known history of asthma, diabetes, or cardiac conditions.\n\n{patientName} has a paternal family history of ADHD. His father was diagnosed in adulthood and manages without medication. His paternal grandfather had a history of alcohol dependence. Lifestyle factors include limited structured physical activity outside of informal play, approximately 2.5 hours of screen time daily, and a diet that is adequate though moderately high in processed foods and sugar."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}